On march 7, 2012
mtp85
Unlocking opens up all of the skills listed under that option, so you can't just unlock First Aid. If you unlocked after getting all of the first level skills, you're okay.

Grouping Dinoz is always advised, for those reasons - especially when they're similar levels. Grouping a level 12 with a level 1 can lead to problems for the level 1 Dinoz, since they'll meet monsters they're not ready for.

The main elements ( on the Softpig, and on the Winks) look pretty good, except for maybe Focus on the Winks. The side elements (everything else) tend to follow one path to reach a specific higher end skill - like Mistral-Unlock-Tornado-Unlock-Vaporous Form in on a Winks, since it leads to the very nice defensive skill Bubble.

On march 20, 2012
Kayin
From CotC Q&A:

What formula is used to calculate a Clan's power?
The Clan's power is based on the 100 most powerful Dinoz in the team.
L = (Level of Dinoz - 1) + half of the spheres equipped on the Dinoz
N = Number of Dinoz in the Clan team
P = SUM (1,L) INT(1.1^(L-1))

Final Power = The sum of the power of the 100 most powerful Dinoz in the team.
To make things easier for you, we invite you to use this spreadsheet showing the power rating corresponding for any level of Dinoz. The left-hand column shows the Dinoz' level and the right-hand column its power.
The DinoRPG Team reserves the right to modify the formula governing the ranking calculations at any time before the combats begin

How is the maximum permissable power calculated during the battle?
This value relates to the average power of the Dinoz in the front lines of the 2 clans.
The first line, which is defined as the 45 most powerful Dinoz that could possibly take to the battlefield.
Therefore, in a battle between clan A and clan B, if the front line of clan A is worth 9000 and the front line of clan B is worth 11000, the maximum power authorised will be (9000+11000)/2, i.e. 10000.

Loppermann
as a general rule (not looking at double skills or whatever), you want to go:
Wrath - unlock - Warm Breath - Burning Heart
Carapace - unlock - Vines - Primal State
Mutation - Ventral Pouch - Sumo
Celerity - Double Hit - Career Plan
Agility - Dodge

the "-"s are unlocks

there are variations of course, some people might choose other skills to suit their overall build or strategy better
e.g. Celerity - Lightning Attack - Hazard is a popular choice too

pretty much the only "non-negociable" one is the path... an extra 130 and another equipment slot will make a huge difference when fighting against other masters

First, I'm not really sure what initiative is. I'd assume it has something to do with going sooner in the turn, but I see both "increases initiative" skills and "increases speed" skills. How do they differ, if at all?
Initiative determines how often your dino attacks, each attack costs initiative so the more you have via skills more often you can attack. Speed is the rate at which dinoz recover initiative. The higher the speed, the more initiative they recover during each round of battle. Out of these two game mechanics I would argue Initiative is the one that plays a bigger role.

BlackAndLoki
@ Kompera

Some skills, such as "Celerity" increase the "speed" of Dino, and others, such as "Hazard" increases the "Initiative". What is the difference between the 2 and how does it work?

Here is the response of support on the subject:

Each fighter has a time value. The fighter with the smallest value performs an attack, then add 10 / Speed at the time. So a fighter with 2.0 attack speed hit twice a fighter with 1.0 attack speed, because each action will cost him 5 points of time instead of 10.


The initiative reduces the value of time at the beginning of combat. Therefore it allows both to perform the first action but also to save time on the other combatants, and a Dino with +10 initiative in comparison with Dino with -10 will almost certainly be able to carry out two attacks before the other. (with 20 time points between them).

In other words, each Dino has a time value, and each time, the one with the smallest value attack, giving for example, start with 2 Dino no boost, so they have a speed of 1, leaving 10 and + 10 are therefore each time (10 / 1 = 10), which gives:

- Dinoz 1 => 10 | Dinoz 2 => 10

- One of two random attack, say Dino 1. He takes 10 points after his attack.

- Dinoz 1 => 20 | Dinoz 2 => 10

- Dino 2 has the smallest value, it attacks, then take 10 time point.

- Dinoz 1 => 20 | Dinoz 2 => 20

- Dino 2 comes to equalize, so it's a Dino 1 attacks and takes 10 points of time.

- Dinoz 1 => 30 | Dinoz 2 => 20

And so on, is what happens to a fight lambda attack once each turn.

Now if Dino 1 has Hazard, he starts with 3 instead of 10, which gives:

- Dinoz 1 => 3 | Dinoz 2 => 10
- Dinoz 1 => 13 | Dinoz 2 => 10
- Dinoz 1 => 13 | Dinoz 2 => 20
- Dinoz 1 => 23 | Dinoz 2 => 20

- Etc..

Now if Dino has a Hazard + Celerity which adds 15% speed so he left with 3 and take this time not 10 points of speed every time, but 10 / (1 +0.15) = 8.7 (rounded to the tenth), this which gives us:

- Dinoz 1 => 3 | Dinoz 2 => 10

- Dinoz 1 => 11.7 | Dinoz 2 => 10

- Dinoz 1 => 11.7 | Dinoz 2 => 20

- Dinoz 1 => 20.4 | Dinoz 2 => 20

- Dinoz 1 => 20.4 | Dinoz 2 => 30

- Dinoz 1 => 29.2 | Dinoz 2 => 30

- Dino 1 a re-attack, as it still has the smallest number.

- Dinoz 1 => 37.9 | Dinoz 2 => 30

- Dino 1 => 37.9 | Dino 2 => 30

- Etc..

Source: french Clan Avis Praeda, they posted it as a log of conversation with a french admin.
Beware that now game motor was changed and it si not 10/ but 100/Speed at the time

And time points calls the velocity points in some other translations.

On march 31, 2012
Wobby
Acid Blood's damage is calculated by Water divided by 7, rounded up.

7 = 1 dmg
8-14 = 2 dmg
15-21 = 3 dmg
22-28 = 4 dmg
29 or higher is 5 damage. I have never seen anything higher than 5, nor do I have any knowledge of a dinoz with 36 or higher.

So as an answer to your original question, 20 and 21 are both 3 damage

Griffinbane
For Winks, Rocky and Wanwan, it's because of their high initiative, speed and useful skills. Rocky and Wanwan both can heal, they can trigger a boost in speed (or initiative, I forget which) which can lead to them single-handedly killing whole teams. All four often carry sets that let them summon clones or korgons as distractions (and clones hit hard!). Winks and Kabuki often carry bubble, which lowers the damage taken from non-direct A skills.
On april 4, 2012
Wobby
I've seen Softpigs hard counter Bubble teams before using Ember, which is another reason why Rockys and Softpigs are so good.
Wanwans and Rockys are the only two dinoz who can regularly achieve 22 Initiative, which using that, they can pull off a huge chain of Initiative moves like Flood and Detonation, which can often result in victory for one side with the opponent not making a move.
Wanwans can be more popular than Rockys because they can get Acrobat, Shock, and a stronger Wood assault than a Rockys Fire assault typically. Wanwans can also have a good shot at Overload, but Sumo is the tricky part.
Typically Winks don't work on Lightning that much. Winks are better than other Water heavy dinoz since they can get early Career Plan and avoid other unnecessary level ups like in Wood after Vines, as well as improving Bubble chances. They can also easily get Hazard, something a Sirain cannot do.
And no, an extremely strong primary element like Santaz or Gorriloz is typically bad, or at least inferior to slightly more spread out Elements.

On april 17, 2012
Oquies

In the dojo what is merit and reputation?
On april 17, 2012
BlackAndLoki

Reputation and Merit are the values upon which your final position in the rankings is decided.

These two values are very different from one another.
Reputation represents a given Dojo's ability to complete the challenges assigned to it.
A Dojo with a strong reputation will have completed a significant number of challenges and have proved its ability to complete the given objectives.

On the other hand, Merit represents the number of battles won in relation to the total number of battles taken on.

The ranking of Dojos takes these txo values into account and is calculated in the following way:

reputation x (no. of battles won / total no. of battles)

The rankings can be accessed via the Dojo Rankings page.

Source is here and read here

Turns do not stack, while you gain turn while resting the turn timer starts ticking again only after you click the New Turn button after you're done with resting. Wo0olfyCan anyone tell me how is normal attak damage calculated ?

The formula for damage is unknown but it is not linear. The only known thing is assault strength and attacks strength. From the assault/attack strength and defences of other dinoz system calculates the damage. There is some random component inside as well. Cause the same assaults/attacks do different damage to the same dinoz. Damage in pvm depends on the fact if monster have a defence or not. In second case damage is equal to assault/attack strength in first case it is the same unknown calculation as for pvp fights. There is a lot of guesses though on a server made by Druid2K for example and other good experienced players, but no confirmed info on subject.

Loppermann

It probably won't sell at the market, but you can either freeze or sacrifice it... but all of your dinoz are a long way off being able to do either of those.
I would suggest keeping the dinoz for now (not like you have a choice anyway ) and continue earning money with it so you can buy more dinoz. Once you have the maximum amount (18, or 21 if you have a dinoz with the skill Leader), the dinoz you don't want should be ready to freeze.
To get to the point you need to freeze you need to do the following:
University -> talk to the professor and learn both climbing and swimming to gain access too the islands and the volcano
Coral mines (south of Frish Port) -> talk to the miner and the get the shovel
Dig at Sticky Swamp, Fountain of Youth and Basalt Slopes (north of precipitous hills) (you need to go back to the coral mines and talk to the miner to repair your shovel after every dig)
Mutant Falls -> talk to Atlanteid Guard
Frish Port -> talk to Joveboze and fight the scorpascuba
Go to Underwater dome and show the ingredients and beat the elemental
Go to the haunted hills (in the forest) and talk to the strage man to get the lantern
THEN you can go to the deep gorges and freeze your dinoz

Well, I'm just starting and my Cloudoz has Strategy, but I haven't really noticed a difference in his attacks. Does 'best attack strategy' mean that it's more likely for my guy to attack with favorable elements, like I thought it was, or is it something else? The wiki isn't terribly helpful on the matter.
On august 30, 2012
BlackAndLoki
DebeshWell, I'm just starting and my Cloudoz has Strategy, but I haven't really noticed a difference in his attacks. Does 'best attack strategy' mean that it's more likely for my guy to attack with favorable elements, like I thought it was, or is it something else? The wiki isn't terribly helpful on the matter.

Without Strategy, the dino attacks first with the strongest assault compared to the other assaults.

With Strategy, it attacks first with the strongest assault compared to the enemy defenses, even if that assault is not the strongest compared to the others. For the next assault it attacks with the second strongest assault, and so on‚Ä¶

The Strategy skill does not choose target for your dino.

F.e
A dino:
Attacks
45, 12, 15, 11, 7

B dino, target 1
Defenses:
20, 10, 32, 21, 5
Attacks order with Strategy: , , , ,
Attacks order without Strategy: , , , ,

fights over devourer: yes, everything is real (fight is in actual hp, losing hp/death are real, items used are lost, etc)

does it worth it:

1.) bambooz has 30hp, so it can survive the first 1-2 attacks, and reduces the chance of vines/liquid stumps/petrifications/hypnosis/black hole in the first 1-3 rounds : and any of these can easily mean a lost battle..

2.) equipping it on a low level dinoz (about level 1-12) mean TONS of help. loosing almost no hp in fights, against elementals, scorbscuba, earth elemental, etc..

3.) in the dojo qualification equip it on level 1-3 dinoz and it will be one autowin without risk..

4.) bambooz works under banishment (capture glove not). captured monsters dies, you have to capture new ones, the bamboo is present at every fight...

Devs usually don't say anything about battle internals. But a lot of things the players already found out on their own. One example for this are dojo fights.

Imagine you have a dino with electrolysis and clones. You let it fight against itself in a dojo test match. Because it's the same dino it has the same speed and will attack alternately. Then one of the dinos creates a clone and the other one not (by bad luck in triggering). Suddenly the dino with the clone begins to attack 2 times in a row sometimes. What else than a speed buff from the clone could be resposible for that?

It seems that clones inherit all the P-skills from their original.

On september 20, 2012
SomeoneSpecial

Endurance (also called Sufferance, Stamina, Resilience, or Durability) is the ability of an organism to exert itself and remain active for a long period of time.

Based on this meaning of endurance, it means dinoz losing energy will lose attacking turns thus will get hit more often and suffer greater damage. Energy is lost by using the dinoz learnt strong skills, so it seems that too powerful dinoz actions will lower energy bar. Resting will restore energy, so when a turn is lost, your energy bar should move up.

On october 24, 2012
Phoenix
Shad0w10What's speed and what's initiative ?

Initiative says when your dinoz comes compared to the other dinoz. It's a random number plus the Initiative of your Dinoz.

The speed is more tricky. Basically when your dinoz gets an action it's Initiative is reduced by some amount. The faster your dinoz, the lower the reduction is. This way a high initiative high speed dinoz get multiple actions before the others so it has higher chance to launch a Flood, Vines, Detonation etc. to lower the opponents' initiative getting even more actions. This is how the stun locks work.

unixasas

The chance is greater for those skills which level is lower, for example, burning breath (2) has greater chance than lava flow (3). However, fire ball (3) and lava flow (3) are at the same level, so the chance here is greater for the skill that is above another in the details tab of your dino. In this case, fireball is higher, thus has the greater chance.

There is basically a percent chance to use an A skill each turn, but it goes by which tier the skill is. Also now endurance complicates this as well, so the way it should work is it will check each tier from 4 to 1, if a skill does trigger then there will be a check to see if you have enough endurance to cast, if you don't then it should continue down to tier one and if you don't have enough endurance/or another A skill doesn't trigger you'll end up just doing an assault.

BlackAndLoki
Shad0w10I calculate that a demon gorilloz, well-built, at level 60 has 300 Wood-Atack, but in IT I didn't saw damadge highter than 50-100... How is it possible? A good defence is maximum 50, not +100...

Well first you obviously calculates defence wrong try to use our tool f.e. to see the defences of different dinoz. Defence can reach 100 even at level 50. F.e. check the numbers of this quetzu


And second the daamge of assault or A-skill is not simple difference between strength and defence it is calculated in other way. F.e. check the guide of one of our top players druid2k

damage is calculated like:
- if your calculated attack (assault, or power of spell) is less than the target's defense, you will deal 1 damage
- if it is about 10-20 points greater, then you will do about (attack/10)*0,2-0.5
- if it is more than 20-30 points greater, then you will deal attack/10
- if it is more than double the defense, then you will deal about attack*0,7-0.8 damage..
(its not a formula, only a guidance..

example:

defense = 80

assault = 70 -> 1 damage
assault = 85 -> 1-3 damage
assault = 90 -> 2-6 damage
assault = 100 -> 8-9 damage
assault = 110 -> 10-12 damage
assault = 160 -> 15-17 damage
assault = 240 -> 20-24 damage
assault = 400 -> 30-35 damage..
